Day 1: Python Fundamentals - Basic Data Types, Operators, Lists & Control Flow (Part 1)

Goal: Get comfortable with basic Python syntax, data storage (variables, lists), and making simple decisions/repetitions in code. This builds the foundation for everything else.

Topics:

Introduction: What is Python? Why use it for Data Analysis? (Briefly)

Basic Syntax: Comments (#), indentation (crucial!).

Variables: Assigning values, naming conventions.

Fundamental Data Types:

Integers (int)

Floating-point numbers (float)

Strings (str) - creation, basic methods (.upper(), .lower(), .strip(), f-strings).

Booleans (bool) - True, False.

Basic Operators:

Arithmetic: +, -, *, /, // (floor division), % (modulo), ** (exponentiation).

Comparison: ==, !=, >, <, >=, <=.

Logical: and, or, not.

Lists:

Creating lists: my_list = [1, "hello", 3.14, True]

Accessing elements: Indexing (starts at 0) my_list[0].

Slicing: my_list[1:3] (gets elements at index 1 and 2).

Modifying lists: Changing elements my_list[1] = "world".

Common List Methods: .append(), .insert(), .pop(), .remove(), .sort(), len().